everybody, let's

00:01:03.650 --> 00:01:07.910 align:middle line:84%
recap the time of the
outsider, the years, and some

00:01:07.910 --> 00:01:10.990 align:middle line:84%
of what you have told us before,
just to set the stage for right

00:01:10.990 --> 00:01:11.790 align:middle line:90%
now.

00:01:11.790 --> 00:01:12.590 align:middle line:90%
>>SIMON: Yeah.

00:01:12.590 --> 00:01:17.180 align:middle line:10%
So we are, the world is
in an outsider lifecycle.

00:01:17.180 --> 00:01:20.840 align:middle line:84%
And what that means is, new
technologies, new philosophies,

00:01:20.840 --> 00:01:22.040 align:middle line:90%
new ideas.

00:01:22.040 --> 00:01:24.080 align:middle line:10%
Out with the old,
in with the new.

00:01:24.080 --> 00:01:28.250 align:middle line:10%
And sometimes the
transition is abrupt.

00:01:28.250 --> 00:01:32.660 align:middle line:84%
And it's always, it can
be very uncomfortable.

00:01:32.660 --> 00:01:35.480 align:middle line:84%
But ultimately,
it's for the good.

00:01:35.480 --> 00:01:38.390 align:middle line:84%
So even though we're in
an uncomfortable time now,

00:01:38.390 --> 00:01:41.953 align:middle line:84%
10, 20 years from now,
these new technologies,

00:01:41.953 --> 00:01:43.370 align:middle line:84%
new things that
are coming in that

00:01:43.370 --> 00:01:49.010 align:middle line:84%
started right around 20,
just before 2016, 2015 or so.

00:01:49.010 --> 00:01:50.960 align:middle line:84%
And we've got about
another 10 years left.

00:01:50.960 --> 00:01:54.303 align:middle line:90%
So it's not over.

00:01:54.303 --> 00:01:55.720 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Well,
it's barely begun.

00:01:55.720 --> 00:01:56.110 align:middle line:90%
>>SIMON: Yeah.

00:01:56.110 --> 00:01:57.670 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: But one
thing I remember

00:01:57.670 --> 00:02:00.760 align:middle line:84%
you saying when we talked
about this once before, is,

00:02:00.760 --> 00:02:01.660 align:middle line:90%
and this was before.

00:02:01.660 --> 00:02:04.420 align:middle line:84%
This, I think, was
in 2019, was you

00:02:04.420 --> 00:02:09.380 align:middle line:84%
said of this cycle, the most
chaotic period of this cycle

00:02:09.380 --> 00:02:11.380 align:middle line:84%
that could be perceived
as chaotic, because it's

00:02:11.380 --> 00:02:14.590 align:middle line:84%
about change, that
the most densely

00:02:14.590 --> 00:02:17.210 align:middle line:84%
saturated chaotic
energy would be in 2020.

00:02:17.210 --> 00:02:18.010 align:middle line:90%
>>SIMON: Yeah.

00:02:18.010 --> 00:02:20.060 align:middle line:90%
And I didn't know why.

00:02:20.060 --> 00:02:22.300 align:middle line:84%
Like what would be
the causative factor.

00:02:22.300 --> 00:02:25.070 align:middle line:84%
And that's kind of the way it
is with outsiders and outsider

00:02:25.070 --> 00:02:25.870 align:middle line:90%
periods.

00:02:25.870 --> 00:02:27.350 align:middle line:90%
It comes out from left field.

00:02:27.350 --> 00:02:29.410 align:middle line:84%
It's the punch, it's the
hook that catches you

00:02:29.410 --> 00:02:31.035 align:middle line:84%
that you don't see
that knocks you out,

00:02:31.035 --> 00:02:32.590 align:middle line:90%
not the one that you see.

00:02:32.590 --> 00:02:34.720 align:middle line:90%
So yeah.

00:02:34.720 --> 00:02:38.500 align:middle line:84%
So this January I made a video
on YouTube about Bitcoin.

00:02:38.500 --> 00:02:42.190 align:middle line:84%
And I said, listen, it's about
to go down about February 9,

00:02:42.190 --> 00:02:43.087 align:middle line:90%
I forget the dates.

00:02:43.087 --> 00:02:44.170 align:middle line:90%
You could see it on there.

00:02:44.170 --> 00:02:47.530 align:middle line:90%
February 20 and then to March.

00:02:47.530 --> 00:02:50.260 align:middle line:84%
And it could be from a terrorist
event, could be from a virus,

00:02:50.260 --> 00:02:53.410 align:middle line:84%
could be from something that
is just so out of the blue

00:02:53.410 --> 00:02:55.130 align:middle line:90%
that it knocks us out.

00:02:55.130 --> 00:02:58.900 align:middle line:84%
And it turned out
to be from a virus.

00:02:58.900 --> 00:03:03.750 align:middle line:84%
And we're still in that
period, we're still

00:03:03.750 --> 00:03:06.480 align:middle line:90%
recovering from that period.

00:03:06.480 --> 00:03:08.640 align:middle line:90%
So it's a crazy year.

00:03:08.640 --> 00:03:11.280 align:middle line:84%
But there is
something good in it.

00:03:11.280 --> 00:03:13.367 align:middle line:90%
There is a huge silver lining.

00:03:13.367 --> 00:03:14.700 align:middle line:90%
And I hope we can talk about it.

00:03:14.700 --> 00:03:16.230 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: I do want to
talk about it, because I

00:03:16.230 --> 00:03:17.490 align:middle line:90%
see it the same way.

00:03:17.490 --> 00:03:21.270 align:middle line:84%
I see it just as the
wake up call for humanity

00:03:21.270 --> 00:03:24.888 align:middle line:84%
to re-evaluate life values,
what really matters,

00:03:24.888 --> 00:03:26.430 align:middle line:84%
even look at the
nature of our health

00:03:26.430 --> 00:03:28.500 align:middle line:84%
and immune system
from a fresh, new more

00:03:28.500 --> 00:03:33.060 align:middle line:84%
responsible way, a bunch
of silver linings it it.

00:03:33.060 --> 00:03:34.085 align:middle line:90%
What are your thoughts?

00:03:34.085 --> 00:03:35.460 align:middle line:84%
Talk about the
silver linings now

00:03:35.460 --> 00:03:36.910 align:middle line:84%
before we go to
some other things.

00:03:36.910 --> 00:03:37.710 align:middle line:90%
>>SIMON: Yeah.

00:03:37.710 --> 00:03:38.640 align:middle line:90%
Relationships.

00:03:38.640 --> 00:03:41.640 align:middle line:84%
It's forcing you to
actually talk to the person

00:03:41.640 --> 00:03:44.910 align:middle line:84%
that you live with, because you
don't get, you're not at work

00:03:44.910 --> 00:03:48.000 align:middle line:84%
eight hours a day and they're
not at work, so you're at home.

00:03:48.000 --> 00:03:51.160 align:middle line:84%
And sometimes it'll
break relationships,

00:03:51.160 --> 00:03:53.860 align:middle line:84%
but it'll definitely
strain relationships, even

00:03:53.860 --> 00:03:54.660 align:middle line:90%
the good ones.

00:03:54.660 --> 00:03:57.750 align:middle line:84%
But out of that strain
comes, it's like a muscle.

00:03:57.750 --> 00:03:59.797 align:middle line:84%
When you work it,
it gets stronger.

00:03:59.797 --> 00:04:02.380 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Well, and if you have
enough strain for long enough,

00:04:02.380 --> 00:04:04.088 align:middle line:84%
you're going to break
down at some point,

00:04:04.088 --> 00:04:06.570 align:middle line:84%
and you're going to go into
kind of conversations or.

00:04:06.570 --> 00:04:07.820 align:middle line:90%
>>SIMON: Honest conversations.

00:04:07.820 --> 00:04:11.070 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Screaming matches
that have deeper truths in them,

00:04:11.070 --> 00:04:13.080 align:middle line:84%
which a lot of people
have been going through.

00:04:13.080 --> 00:04:17.297 align:middle line:84%
And of course, it's straining
the court dockets for divorces

00:04:17.297 --> 00:04:18.880 align:middle line:84%
right now, because
so many people want

00:04:18.880 --> 00:04:20.490 align:middle line:84%
to, now that
they've spoken, want

00:04:20.490 --> 00:04:22.019 align:middle line:90%
to get away from each other.

00:04:22.019 --> 00:04:24.270 align:middle line:84%
But others have really come
down to the nitty gritty

00:04:24.270 --> 00:04:26.330 align:middle line:90%
of where the differences were.

00:04:26.330 --> 00:04:28.440 align:middle line:84%
>>SIMON: Well, better
sooner than later.

00:04:28.440 --> 00:04:31.200 align:middle line:84%
If the divorce is coming,
just get it over with now.

00:04:31.200 --> 00:04:32.130 align:middle line:90%
Pop that pimple.

00:04:32.130 --> 00:04:34.615 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Pop the pimple
or allow yourself, now

00:04:34.615 --> 00:04:36.990 align:middle line:84%
that you've gotten to it, to
go into the healing of that.

00:04:36.990 --> 00:04:38.160 align:middle line:90%
>>SIMON: Yeah.

00:04:38.160 --> 00:04:39.980 align:middle line:84%
So that's one of
the silver linings.

00:04:39.980 --> 00:04:44.610 align:middle line:84%
Another is just to see
how fragile we are.

00:04:44.610 --> 00:04:46.830 align:middle line:84%
As a society, we
depend on electricity.

00:04:46.830 --> 00:04:49.020 align:middle line:84%
What happens if that
electricity goes out?

00:04:49.020 --> 00:04:51.330 align:middle line:84%
What happens if we
can't go to work?

00:04:51.330 --> 00:04:54.810 align:middle line:84%
But even as human
beings, if we can't

00:04:54.810 --> 00:04:59.080 align:middle line:84%
interact with one another,
how that affects us socially.

00:04:59.080 --> 00:05:01.380 align:middle line:84%
Like a lot of people
are really realizing

00:05:01.380 --> 00:05:03.390 align:middle line:84%
that they're depressed
if they're not around

00:05:03.390 --> 00:05:04.432 align:middle line:90%
friends and other humans.

00:05:04.432 --> 00:05:07.763 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Extroverts, this
has been hell for extroverts.

00:05:07.763 --> 00:05:09.180 align:middle line:84%
>>SIMON: I'm more
of an introvert,

00:05:09.180 --> 00:05:10.470 align:middle line:90%
so for me it's like, corona?

00:05:10.470 --> 00:05:11.270 align:middle line:90%
What corona?

00:05:11.270 --> 00:05:12.070 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yeah.

00:05:12.070 --> 00:05:14.263 align:middle line:84%
>>SIMON: But because I
mostly work from home,

00:05:14.263 --> 00:05:15.430 align:middle line:90%
and it's that type of thing.

00:05:15.430 --> 00:05:19.467 align:middle line:84%
But my friends who are more of
the extroverts are going nuts.

00:05:19.467 --> 00:05:21.800 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Oh, I have one
friend who's, I'm an introvert,

00:05:21.800 --> 00:05:22.720 align:middle line:90%
so I work from home.

00:05:22.720 --> 00:05:23.520 align:middle line:90%
>>SIMON: Yeah.

00:05:23.520 --> 00:05:25.060 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: And I
live in the country.

00:05:25.060 --> 00:05:25.400 align:middle line:90%
>>SIMON: Yeah.

00:05:25.400 --> 00:05:26.880 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: I have my favorite
little coffee shops,

00:05:26.880 --> 00:05:27.760 align:middle line:90%
they're still open.

00:05:27.760 --> 00:05:27.990 align:middle line:90%
>>SIMON: Yeah.

00:05:27.990 --> 00:05:29.190 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: I can go
to if I want to.

00:05:29.190 --> 00:05:30.340 align:middle line:90%
And I go on my bike ride.

00:05:30.340 --> 00:05:33.240 align:middle line:84%
So life hasn't really
changed much for me at all.

00:05:33.240 --> 00:05:36.180 align:middle line:84%
But oh my God, one
friend in particular,

00:05:36.180 --> 00:05:39.670 align:middle line:84%
she just calls up in full
on panic and anxiety.

00:05:39.670 --> 00:05:41.463 align:middle line:84%
Everybody's canceling
every event!

00:05:41.463 --> 00:05:42.630 align:middle line:90%
I don't know where I can go.

00:05:42.630 --> 00:05:44.922 align:middle line:84%
I can't believe they're not
going to show up for lunch.

00:05:44.922 --> 00:05:49.380 align:middle line:84%
And just panic stricken at the
lack of human companionship.

00:05:49.380 --> 00:05:52.483 align:middle line:84%
And I, I mean, it's really
causing her mass anxiety.

00:05:52.483 --> 00:05:54.900 align:middle line:84%
I don't know the percentages,
but at least half the planet

00:05:54.900 --> 00:05:55.720 align:middle line:90%
have to be extroverts.

00:05:55.720 --> 00:05:56.520 align:middle line:90%
>>SIMON: Sure.

00:05:56.520 --> 00:05:58.080 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Really suffering.

00:05:58.080 --> 00:05:59.520 align:middle line:90%
And what about kids?

00:05:59.520 --> 00:06:00.420 align:middle line:90%
>>SIMON: Yeah.

00:06:00.420 --> 00:06:04.590 align:middle line:84%
Well, this is where knowing who
you are comes in very handy.

00:06:04.590 --> 00:06:06.040 align:middle line:90%
When you understand who you are.

00:06:06.040 --> 00:06:09.270 align:middle line:84%
And that's why I do astrology,
because you can look

00:06:09.270 --> 00:06:10.770 align:middle line:90%
at your chart and you go, huh.

00:06:10.770 --> 00:06:12.755 align:middle line:84%
OK, that's how this
is affecting me.

00:06:12.755 --> 00:06:14.130 align:middle line:84%
All right, how do
I deal with it?

00:06:14.130 --> 00:06:17.010 align:middle line:84%
Like right now, I
have knee problems.

00:06:17.010 --> 00:06:19.550 align:middle line:84%
And it's right
there in my chart.

00:06:19.550 --> 00:06:22.920 align:middle line:84%
For the next six months, you're
going to have knee problems.

00:06:22.920 --> 00:06:24.510 align:middle line:90%
OK, right on time.

00:06:24.510 --> 00:06:29.220 align:middle line:84%
It sucks, it's terrible, but
you know that there's a tunnel.

00:06:29.220 --> 00:06:30.640 align:middle line:90%
You're going to get out of it.

00:06:30.640 --> 00:06:33.120 align:middle line:84%
So same thing with
your extrovert friends.

00:06:33.120 --> 00:06:36.900 align:middle line:84%
You could just say,
listen, this is temporary.

00:06:36.900 --> 00:06:38.360 align:middle line:90%
It's about to be over.

00:06:38.360 --> 00:06:41.330 align:middle line:84%
So prepare for when
it is over and how

00:06:41.330 --> 00:06:42.950 align:middle line:90%
you can celebrate those times.

00:06:42.950 --> 00:06:45.650 align:middle line:84%
Because people, we take
our freedom for granted.

00:06:45.650 --> 00:06:47.180 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yes.

00:06:47.180 --> 00:06:50.480 align:middle line:84%
>>SIMON: When it's taken away
from us, we go, oh, crap.

00:06:50.480 --> 00:06:51.620 align:middle line:90%
This sucks.

00:06:51.620 --> 00:06:53.420 align:middle line:90%
So be ready to celebrate it.

00:06:53.420 --> 00:06:54.220 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yes.

00:06:54.220 --> 00:06:56.012 align:middle line:84%
And I think the other
thing that has really

00:06:56.012 --> 00:06:59.450 align:middle line:84%
come out of this too, is
how you can do work-arounds.

00:06:59.450 --> 00:07:03.320 align:middle line:84%
For example, a lot of people
have turned to Zoom or Skype

00:07:03.320 --> 00:07:05.630 align:middle line:84%
to do these group
family, group friendship

00:07:05.630 --> 00:07:08.090 align:middle line:84%
calls on a regular
basis to satisfy

00:07:08.090 --> 00:07:10.340 align:middle line:84%
that need for connection
and seeing someone's face.

00:07:10.340 --> 00:07:12.155 align:middle line:84%
And that's something
that's come out of it.

00:07:12.155 --> 00:07:14.080 align:middle line:84%
Of course, it's caused
some problems for Zoom,

00:07:14.080 --> 00:07:15.780 align:middle line:84%
but they're getting up
to speed technologically.

00:07:15.780 --> 00:07:16.700 align:middle line:90%
>>SIMON: Yeah.

00:07:16.700 --> 00:07:18.440 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: The point
is, that people

00:07:18.440 --> 00:07:21.290 align:middle line:84%
have found innovative
ways to still satisfy that

00:07:21.290 --> 00:07:23.180 align:middle line:90%
to an extent.

00:07:23.180 --> 00:07:25.050 align:middle line:84%
>>SIMON: Thank God
for Alex Mashinsky.

00:07:25.050 --> 00:07:25.850 align:middle line:90%
You know?

00:07:25.850 --> 00:07:27.170 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Who's Alex?

00:07:27.170 --> 00:07:31.310 align:middle line:84%
>>SIMON: Alex is a
Ukrainian-born entrepreneur who

00:07:31.310 --> 00:07:33.200 align:middle line:90%
invented voice over internet.

00:07:33.200 --> 00:07:35.430 align:middle line:90%
This is way back in the '90s.

00:07:35.430 --> 00:07:36.620 align:middle line:90%
He has the patents.

00:07:36.620 --> 00:07:38.870 align:middle line:84%
And he said, I'm
going to take away

00:07:38.870 --> 00:07:40.903 align:middle line:84%
the power of AT&T and
Verizon, because it

00:07:40.903 --> 00:07:43.070 align:middle line:84%
used to be like $3 bucks a
minute, $2 bucks a minute

00:07:43.070 --> 00:07:45.230 align:middle line:90%
to talk to people.

00:07:45.230 --> 00:07:46.065 align:middle line:90%
Now it's free.

00:07:46.065 --> 00:07:47.690 align:middle line:84%
So we can all talk
over Zoom and Skype.

00:07:47.690 --> 00:07:48.530 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Thank god.

00:07:48.530 --> 00:07:51.500 align:middle line:84%
>>SIMON: And his
next invention now

00:07:51.500 --> 00:07:55.020 align:middle line:84%
is something called the Celsius
app, which is, by the way,

00:07:55.020 --> 00:07:58.075 align:middle line:84%
I'm not a, I'm not a paid
spokesperson or anything,

00:07:58.075 --> 00:07:59.200 align:middle line:90%
but I use it and I love it.

00:07:59.200 --> 00:08:00.560 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: What is it?

00:08:00.560 --> 00:08:04.960 align:middle line:84%
>>SIMON: It's, he calls
it, money over internet.

00:08:04.960 --> 00:08:05.850 align:middle line:90%
It's his big--

00:08:05.850 --> 00:08:06.330 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: What is that?

00:08:06.330 --> 00:08:08.670 align:middle line:84%
I mean, how is that compared
to some of the others that

00:08:08.670 --> 00:08:10.378 align:middle line:90%
exist, like Venmo and all?

00:08:10.378 --> 00:08:12.420 align:middle line:84%
>>SIMON: Well, this,
because it's cryptocurrency.

00:08:12.420 --> 00:08:13.220 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Oh.

00:08:13.220 --> 00:08:15.130 align:middle line:84%
>>SIMON: And this is
the other big innovation

00:08:15.130 --> 00:08:15.930 align:middle line:90%
that's happening.

00:08:15.930 --> 00:08:17.220 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: We're going to
talk about money, yes.

00:08:17.220 --> 00:08:20.240 align:middle line:84%
>>SIMON: In this outsider period
is the revolution of money,

00:08:20.240 --> 00:08:20.470 align:middle line:90%
right?

00:08:20.470 --> 00:08:21.270 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: OK.

00:08:21.270 --> 00:08:24.240 align:middle line:84%
>>SIMON: And how
we have the ability

00:08:24.240 --> 00:08:27.420 align:middle line:84%
to take power over our own
finances with cryptocurrency

00:08:27.420 --> 00:08:29.970 align:middle line:84%
rather than it being owned
by the banks and even

00:08:29.970 --> 00:08:30.840 align:middle line:90%
the government fiat.

00:08:30.840 --> 00:08:34.919 align:middle line:84%
So Alex Mashinsky has
an app called Celsius,

00:08:34.919 --> 00:08:38.950 align:middle line:84%
and it lets you earn 10%
interest on your dollars

00:08:38.950 --> 00:08:39.750 align:middle line:90%
basically.

00:08:39.750 --> 00:08:42.580 align:middle line:84%
So he's saying, hey, we used
to have savings accounts,

00:08:42.580 --> 00:08:43.380 align:middle line:90%
now we don't.

00:08:43.380 --> 00:08:45.430 align:middle line:84%
I want to put them back
in the hands of people.

00:08:45.430 --> 00:08:47.910 align:middle line:84%
So what he did with
voice over internet,

00:08:47.910 --> 00:08:50.040 align:middle line:84%
he's doing with
money over internet.

00:08:50.040 --> 00:08:51.400 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: How does it work?

00:08:51.400 --> 00:08:54.120 align:middle line:84%
>>SIMON: So you have
$100, you convert

00:08:54.120 --> 00:08:59.340 align:middle line:84%
that into a digital crypto, like
in the US, it's called Tether.

00:08:59.340 --> 00:09:00.840 align:middle line:90%
Or you can buy Bitcoin.

00:09:00.840 --> 00:09:02.700 align:middle line:84%
You can buy any of
the cryptocurrencies,

00:09:02.700 --> 00:09:04.560 align:middle line:84%
and you just put
them in that wallet.

00:09:04.560 --> 00:09:07.020 align:middle line:84%
So the wallet is
like a bank account.

00:09:07.020 --> 00:09:08.490 align:middle line:84%
And it immediately
starts earning.

00:09:08.490 --> 00:09:12.590 align:middle line:90%
So Bitcoin earns around 4%, 5%.

00:09:12.590 --> 00:09:15.720 align:middle line:84%
The one that's 1 to 1 to the
dollar, so if have $100 bucks,

00:09:15.720 --> 00:09:18.340 align:middle line:84%
you buy $100 Tether,
it's called Tether.

00:09:18.340 --> 00:09:22.220 align:middle line:90%
Earns you about 8%, 9% I think.

00:09:22.220 --> 00:09:23.470 align:middle line:90%
I mean, depending on the week.

00:09:23.470 --> 00:09:25.300 align:middle line:90%
And you just get that in kind.

00:09:25.300 --> 00:09:26.590 align:middle line:90%
And it's compounded interest.

00:09:26.590 --> 00:09:28.240 align:middle line:84%
Like Einstein said,
compound interest

00:09:28.240 --> 00:09:31.000 align:middle line:84%
is one of most powerful
forces in the universe.

00:09:31.000 --> 00:09:32.920 align:middle line:84%
It's weird that we're
talking about that now,

00:09:32.920 --> 00:09:37.420 align:middle line:84%
but just came to my mind
that during outsider times,

00:09:37.420 --> 00:09:40.180 align:middle line:84%
we get innovative
solutions to problems

00:09:40.180 --> 00:09:41.750 align:middle line:90%
we didn't even know we had.

00:09:41.750 --> 00:09:42.550 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yeah.

00:09:42.550 --> 00:09:44.950 align:middle line:84%
>>SIMON: Because you give
your $100 bucks to the bank,

00:09:44.950 --> 00:09:47.710 align:middle line:84%
they loan it out and they
make 15% to 20% interest

00:09:47.710 --> 00:09:48.730 align:middle line:90%
for credit card debt.

00:09:48.730 --> 00:09:49.630 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: You make nothing.

00:09:49.630 --> 00:09:51.088 align:middle line:84%
>>SIMON: You not
only make nothing,

00:09:51.088 --> 00:09:52.870 align:middle line:90%
but you're charged fees.

00:09:52.870 --> 00:09:56.090 align:middle line:84%
When you have a
transfer fee, there's

00:09:56.090 --> 00:09:59.347 align:middle line:84%
an overdraft fee, underdraft
fee, middle draft fee,

00:09:59.347 --> 00:10:00.430 align:middle line:90%
there's all kinds of fees.

00:10:00.430 --> 00:10:01.230 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yeah.

00:10:01.230 --> 00:10:03.370 align:middle line:84%
>>SIMON: So those fees
are in the billions.

00:10:03.370 --> 00:10:05.695 align:middle line:84%
I think $60 billion
a year collectively.

00:10:05.695 --> 00:10:06.520 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yeah.

00:10:06.520 --> 00:10:08.590 align:middle line:84%
>>SIMON: And they
don't get paid to you,

00:10:08.590 --> 00:10:10.340 align:middle line:84%
they get paid to
the bank investors.

00:10:10.340 --> 00:10:14.080 align:middle line:84%
So what Mashinky's saying, hey,
you should get that interest.

00:10:14.080 --> 00:10:21.485 align:middle line:84%
So he's giving people more
of a share of their savings

00:10:21.485 --> 00:10:22.610 align:middle line:90%
than the bank account does.

00:10:22.610 --> 00:10:24.235 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: So how does
this work though?

00:10:24.235 --> 00:10:26.260 align:middle line:84%
So you take your $100
of old style money.

00:10:26.260 --> 00:10:27.040 align:middle line:90%
>>SIMON: Fiat money, right.

00:10:27.040 --> 00:10:27.760 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yeah, fiat money.

00:10:27.760 --> 00:10:28.593 align:middle line:90%
>>SIMON: US dollars.

00:10:28.593 --> 00:10:31.200 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: And then you
invest in say, $100.

00:10:31.200 --> 00:10:32.500 align:middle line:90%
>>SIMON: You buy $100 worth.

00:10:32.500 --> 00:10:32.740 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Tether.

00:10:32.740 --> 00:10:33.370 align:middle line:90%
>>SIMON: Of Tether.

00:10:33.370 --> 00:10:33.760 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Of Tether.

00:10:33.760 --> 00:10:35.218 align:middle line:84%
>>SIMON: Which is
still worth $100.

00:10:35.218 --> 00:10:37.450 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: And now it's
earning say 8% or 9%.

00:10:37.450 --> 00:10:39.940 align:middle line:84%
How do you, how are you
able to use it functionally?

00:10:39.940 --> 00:10:40.930 align:middle line:90%
>>SIMON: You don't.

00:10:40.930 --> 00:10:42.880 align:middle line:84%
So when you want
that as money again,

00:10:42.880 --> 00:10:43.720 align:middle line:84%
you convert it back
into US dollars.

00:10:43.720 --> 00:10:44.240 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: That's what
I was going to ask.

00:10:44.240 --> 00:10:46.630 align:middle line:84%
So you can convert it
back to fiat currency.

00:10:46.630 --> 00:10:47.430 align:middle line:90%
>>SIMON: That's it.

00:10:47.430 --> 00:10:47.790 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: OK.

00:10:47.790 --> 00:10:48.220 align:middle line:90%
Interesting.

00:10:48.220 --> 00:10:50.137 align:middle line:84%
>>SIMON: So if you want
to hold it for a year,

00:10:50.137 --> 00:10:52.360 align:middle line:84%
there are no penalties,
there are no fees.

00:10:52.360 --> 00:10:53.470 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: That's cool.

00:10:53.470 --> 00:10:54.940 align:middle line:84%
>>SIMON: It is very
cool, isn't it?

00:10:54.940 --> 00:10:55.740 align:middle line:90%
And I love it.

00:10:55.740 --> 00:10:59.800 align:middle line:90%
I've got, I'm invested in that.

00:10:59.800 --> 00:11:01.930 align:middle line:84%
Because the way, and
this is something

00:11:01.930 --> 00:11:04.480 align:middle line:84%
that we can talk about,
the monetary system

00:11:04.480 --> 00:11:09.558 align:middle line:84%
is being revamped
right under our noses.

00:11:09.558 --> 00:11:12.100 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: And we're going to,
right, let's go right into that

00:11:12.100 --> 00:11:14.870 align:middle line:84%
after this, because
cryptocurrency is part of it.

00:11:14.870 --> 00:11:17.260 align:middle line:84%
I think what scares most
people about cryptocurrency

00:11:17.260 --> 00:11:19.970 align:middle line:84%
has been the historic
volatility of it.

00:11:19.970 --> 00:11:21.940 align:middle line:84%
So how does that
factor in Celsius?

00:11:21.940 --> 00:11:22.950 align:middle line:90%
You just?

00:11:22.950 --> 00:11:23.750 align:middle line:90%
>>SIMON: Right.

00:11:23.750 --> 00:11:26.350 align:middle line:84%
So if you want, if you think
a certain crypto is going up,

00:11:26.350 --> 00:11:27.730 align:middle line:90%
invest in it like Bitcoin.

00:11:27.730 --> 00:11:32.950 align:middle line:84%
So Bitcoin is, from the
beginning of this year,

00:11:32.950 --> 00:11:36.910 align:middle line:84%
2020, has outpaced gold, has
doubled the value of gold

00:11:36.910 --> 00:11:38.330 align:middle line:90%
in terms of return.

00:11:38.330 --> 00:11:40.760 align:middle line:84%
But if you're not comfortable,
because it does definitely

00:11:40.760 --> 00:11:41.110 align:middle line:90%
go up.

00:11:41.110 --> 00:11:42.030 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: It does,
oh, yeah, yeah.

00:11:42.030 --> 00:11:44.170 align:middle line:84%
>>SIMON: Then just get
something called Tether,

00:11:44.170 --> 00:11:45.790 align:middle line:90%
which is called a stable coin.

00:11:45.790 --> 00:11:47.920 align:middle line:84%
And there are a
few stable coins.

00:11:47.920 --> 00:11:51.700 align:middle line:90%
USDC, USDT, which is the Tether.

00:11:51.700 --> 00:11:53.770 align:middle line:84%
And that is linked
to the dollar 1 to 1.

00:11:53.770 --> 00:11:55.200 align:middle line:90%
It never, it won't vary.

00:11:55.200 --> 00:11:55.570 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: OK.

00:11:55.570 --> 00:11:57.910 align:middle line:84%
>>SIMON: So you know for sure
that you put $100 bucks in,

00:11:57.910 --> 00:11:59.490 align:middle line:84%
you're going to have
$100 bucks coming out.

00:11:59.490 --> 00:11:59.860 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: OK.

00:11:59.860 --> 00:12:02.530 align:middle line:84%
>>SIMON: The only difference
is, you get 8%, 9%, sometimes

00:12:02.530 --> 00:12:03.520 align:middle line:90%
10% interest on it.

00:12:03.520 --> 00:12:04.650 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: That's very cool.

00:12:04.650 --> 00:12:06.400 align:middle line:84%
>>SIMON: If you think
Bitcoin is going up,

00:12:06.400 --> 00:12:07.483 align:middle line:90%
and I think it's going up.

00:12:07.483 --> 00:12:08.560 align:middle line:90%
We've begun the bull run.

00:12:08.560 --> 00:12:11.078 align:middle line:84%
I've been pretty dead
on about Bitcoin's.

00:12:11.078 --> 00:12:12.120 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Astrologically.

00:12:12.120 --> 00:12:12.750 align:middle line:90%
>>SIMON: Astrologically.

00:12:12.750 --> 00:12:13.780 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Charting it, yeah.

00:12:13.780 --> 00:12:16.322 align:middle line:84%
>>SIMON: Sometimes to the day
about its movements up and down

00:12:16.322 --> 00:12:17.545 align:middle line:90%
this year.

00:12:17.545 --> 00:12:19.420 align:middle line:84%
Some other things I
haven't been right about,

00:12:19.420 --> 00:12:21.730 align:middle line:84%
but Bitcoin I've been
pretty accurate with.

00:12:21.730 --> 00:12:24.340 align:middle line:84%
I think the bull
run started July 24.

00:12:24.340 --> 00:12:25.840 align:middle line:90%
I predicted it would jump up.

00:12:25.840 --> 00:12:26.740 align:middle line:90%
It had a little rise.

00:12:26.740 --> 00:12:28.660 align:middle line:90%
It's continued to rise.

00:12:28.660 --> 00:12:31.330 align:middle line:84%
But I think Bitcoin's
bull run has started.

00:12:31.330 --> 00:12:33.940 align:middle line:84%
So if you like the idea
of putting $100 bucks

00:12:33.940 --> 00:12:37.200 align:middle line:84%
in and maybe in a year or two
it it's going to be $200 bucks,

00:12:37.200 --> 00:12:38.950 align:middle line:84%
then you invest in
something like Bitcoin.

00:12:38.950 --> 00:12:41.680 align:middle line:84%
But if you're conservative,
you just put it into Tether.

00:12:41.680 --> 00:12:43.420 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Get $110 back.

00:12:43.420 --> 00:12:44.900 align:middle line:84%
>>SIMON: And you get $110
back at the end of the year,

00:12:44.900 --> 00:12:45.320 align:middle line:90%
and it's compounded.

00:12:45.320 --> 00:12:46.810 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: And it's compounded.

00:12:46.810 --> 00:12:47.610 align:middle line:90%
Interesting.

00:12:47.610 --> 00:12:50.110 align:middle line:84%
OK, let's talk
about, you're saying

00:12:50.110 --> 00:12:51.850 align:middle line:84%
in terms of the
astrology and looking

00:12:51.850 --> 00:12:55.030 align:middle line:84%
at it, that cryptocurrency
has looked like this might

00:12:55.030 --> 00:13:00.010 align:middle line:84%
be the time to start taking
them more seriously as what's

00:13:00.010 --> 00:13:03.310 align:middle line:84%
going to become a normal
part of our economic picture

00:13:03.310 --> 00:13:04.277 align:middle line:90%
in the future?

00:13:04.277 --> 00:13:05.110 align:middle line:90%
>>SIMON: Well, yeah.

00:13:05.110 --> 00:13:08.230 align:middle line:84%
And a lot of, some of the
biggest investment firms

00:13:08.230 --> 00:13:12.160 align:middle line:84%
are already on board,
spending hundreds of millions

00:13:12.160 --> 00:13:14.020 align:middle line:90%
of dollars buying Bitcoin.

00:13:14.020 --> 00:13:17.080 align:middle line:84%
It's not the retail investor
like it was in 2017.

00:13:17.080 --> 00:13:18.250 align:middle line:90%
Retail, I mean you and I.

00:13:18.250 --> 00:13:18.820 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yeah.

00:13:18.820 --> 00:13:20.170 align:middle line:84%
>>SIMON: It's the
big institutions

00:13:20.170 --> 00:13:21.430 align:middle line:90%
that are gobbling up Bitcoin.

00:13:21.430 --> 00:13:23.990 align:middle line:84%
And they're doing it
behind the scenes.

00:13:23.990 --> 00:13:30.520 align:middle line:84%
So in fact, even back in 2018,
like Jamie Dimon, the big CEO,

00:13:30.520 --> 00:13:32.440 align:middle line:90%
was saying Bitcoin is worthless.

00:13:32.440 --> 00:13:34.500 align:middle line:84%
But behind the scenes,
they were buying it up.

00:13:34.500 --> 00:13:35.080 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: They were investing.

00:13:35.080 --> 00:13:35.890 align:middle line:90%
>>SIMON: Yeah.

00:13:35.890 --> 00:13:38.370 align:middle line:84%
So they do that, because
then later on, they'll say,

00:13:38.370 --> 00:13:39.370 align:middle line:90%
oh, we changed our mind.

00:13:39.370 --> 00:13:40.150 align:middle line:90%
And here, oh guess what.

00:13:40.150 --> 00:13:41.430 align:middle line:90%
We have some to offer you.

00:13:41.430 --> 00:13:43.090 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yeah, we own it.

00:13:43.090 --> 00:13:46.010 align:middle line:84%
>>SIMON: So there's huge
institutional interest

00:13:46.010 --> 00:13:46.810 align:middle line:90%
at the moment.

00:13:46.810 --> 00:13:51.400 align:middle line:84%
And it's going, it'll
never be mainstream,

00:13:51.400 --> 00:13:54.460 align:middle line:84%
because it's an alternative
to government money.

00:13:54.460 --> 00:13:56.430 align:middle line:84%
But it's becoming
more mainstream.

00:13:56.430 --> 00:13:59.230 align:middle line:84%
Robert Kiyosaki, the
Rich Dad, Poor Dad guy,

00:13:59.230 --> 00:14:00.940 align:middle line:90%
he's more like rich grandpa now.

00:14:00.940 --> 00:14:01.210 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yeah.

00:14:01.210 --> 00:14:03.002 align:middle line:84%
>>SIMON: But he's still
out there fighting,

00:14:03.002 --> 00:14:05.440 align:middle line:84%
and God bless him, he's
doing a great service.

00:14:05.440 --> 00:14:09.550 align:middle line:84%
He has this thing where
gold and silver he says

00:14:09.550 --> 00:14:12.220 align:middle line:84%
are God's money, because they
were here before we were here.

00:14:12.220 --> 00:14:12.700 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Right

00:14:12.700 --> 00:14:13.500 align:middle line:90%
>>SIMON: Right?

00:14:13.500 --> 00:14:16.250 align:middle line:90%
They're in the Earth.

00:14:16.250 --> 00:14:19.220 align:middle line:84%
Dollars are government
money, because they're issued

00:14:19.220 --> 00:14:20.677 align:middle line:90%
by a decree of the government.

00:14:20.677 --> 00:14:22.010 align:middle line:90%
That's what the word fiat means.

00:14:22.010 --> 00:14:24.140 align:middle line:84%
It's the imperative
case, I believe in Latin.

00:14:24.140 --> 00:14:25.310 align:middle line:90%
Let it be made.

00:14:25.310 --> 00:14:25.640 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yeah.

00:14:25.640 --> 00:14:27.598 align:middle line:84%
>>SIMON: Someone says,
let's make $100 million,

00:14:27.598 --> 00:14:29.270 align:middle line:90%
and it's done.

00:14:29.270 --> 00:14:31.310 align:middle line:84%
But Bitcoin is the
people's money,

00:14:31.310 --> 00:14:34.670 align:middle line:84%
because banks can't control it,
government can't control it,

00:14:34.670 --> 00:14:36.090 align:middle line:90%
it's peer to peer.

00:14:36.090 --> 00:14:39.440 align:middle line:84%
So this is the financial
revolution that's

00:14:39.440 --> 00:14:40.725 align:middle line:90%
coming in this outsider time.

00:14:40.725 --> 00:14:42.100 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Because
a lot of people

00:14:42.100 --> 00:14:43.520 align:middle line:84%
have been afraid to
even get into it.

00:14:43.520 --> 00:14:45.630 align:middle line:84%
Because like I said, of
this volatility and saying,

00:14:45.630 --> 00:14:47.588 align:middle line:84%
well, wait a minute, I
can't buy shoes with it.

00:14:47.588 --> 00:14:49.130 align:middle line:84%
>>SIMON: Can't
buy, yeah, not yet.

00:14:49.130 --> 00:14:51.047 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: But this is
important to know about.

00:14:51.047 --> 00:14:53.002 align:middle line:84%
This sounds like
Celsius is a real segue.

00:14:53.002 --> 00:14:53.960 align:middle line:90%
>>SIMON: It is a segue.

00:14:53.960 --> 00:14:55.010 align:middle line:90%
And here's the thing.

00:14:55.010 --> 00:14:56.150 align:middle line:84%
You don't want to
buy shoes with it.

00:14:56.150 --> 00:14:58.010 align:middle line:84%
Because there's a guy
back in, what was it?

00:14:58.010 --> 00:14:59.840 align:middle line:84%
2014 or something,
who bought two

00:14:59.840 --> 00:15:02.600 align:middle line:90%
pizzas with a bunch of Bitcoin.

00:15:02.600 --> 00:15:04.960 align:middle line:84%
That Bitcoin is worth a
million dollars right now.

00:15:04.960 --> 00:15:05.760 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Right.

00:15:05.760 --> 00:15:07.130 align:middle line:84%
>>SIMON: So you don't want
to buy anything with it.

00:15:07.130 --> 00:15:07.780 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Expensive pizza.

00:15:07.780 --> 00:15:09.240 align:middle line:90%
>>SIMON: It's a store of value.

00:15:09.240 --> 00:15:10.040 align:middle line:90%
It's like gold.

00:15:10.040 --> 00:15:14.495 align:middle line:84%
You don't carry out a gold
brick to the coffee shop and go,

00:15:14.495 --> 00:15:16.370 align:middle line:84%
how much is, and they
shave off a little bit.

00:15:16.370 --> 00:15:17.170 align:middle line:90%
There you go.

00:15:17.170 --> 00:15:18.790 align:middle line:90%
That's, keep the tip, right?

00:15:18.790 --> 00:15:19.660 align:middle line:90%
And put it back in.

00:15:19.660 --> 00:15:21.180 align:middle line:90%
You don't spend it that way.

00:15:21.180 --> 00:15:22.700 align:middle line:84%
So Bitcoin is more
a store of value.

00:15:22.700 --> 00:15:25.640 align:middle line:84%
But some cryptocurrencies
are moving

00:15:25.640 --> 00:15:28.440 align:middle line:84%
in the direction of being
able to be spent as currency.

00:15:28.440 --> 00:15:29.462 align:middle line:90%
So they're credit cards.

00:15:29.462 --> 00:15:30.920 align:middle line:84%
I've got one in my
wallet right now

00:15:30.920 --> 00:15:32.530 align:middle line:90%
that you can spend your crypto.

00:15:32.530 --> 00:15:33.350 align:middle line:90%
But I don't use it.

00:15:33.350 --> 00:15:34.540 align:middle line:90%
I don't want to spend my crypto.

00:15:34.540 --> 00:15:34.820 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Right.

00:15:34.820 --> 00:15:36.380 align:middle line:84%
>>SIMON: I want it to
grow, because it's just

00:15:36.380 --> 00:15:37.400 align:middle line:90%
in the nascent phase.

00:15:37.400 --> 00:15:40.590 align:middle line:84%
We are just beginning
the next bull run.

00:15:40.590 --> 00:15:41.390 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: OK.

00:15:41.390 --> 00:15:44.390 align:middle line:84%
Now we're going to talk a little
bit about how old school Warren

00:15:44.390 --> 00:15:45.690 align:middle line:90%
Buffett's seeing all this.

00:15:45.690 --> 00:15:46.490 align:middle line:90%
>>SIMON: Yeah.

00:15:46.490 --> 00:15:48.710 align:middle line:10%
So Warren Buffett
used to be very much

00:15:48.710 --> 00:15:50.330 align:middle line:10%
against God's money, gold.

00:15:50.330 --> 00:15:53.120 align:middle line:10%
But they just revealed
that June of this year,

00:15:53.120 --> 00:15:54.770 align:middle line:10%
he invested a lot
of money in gold.

00:15:54.770 --> 00:15:55.760 align:middle line:10%
>>REGINA: That's
what I've read too.

00:15:55.760 --> 00:15:56.240 align:middle line:90%
>>SIMON: Yeah.

00:15:56.240 --> 00:15:57.040 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: A lot.

00:15:57.040 --> 00:16:00.162 align:middle line:84%
>>SIMON: So what that means,
is he has no confidence in the.

00:16:00.162 --> 00:16:01.370 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Traditional market.

00:16:01.370 --> 00:16:02.060 align:middle line:90%
>>SIMON: Traditional markets.

00:16:02.060 --> 00:16:03.352 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: The government, yeah.

00:16:03.352 --> 00:16:04.700 align:middle line:90%
>>SIMON: In traditional money.

00:16:04.700 --> 00:16:08.450 align:middle line:84%
So he's not behind Bitcoin,
but it's a matter of time.

00:16:08.450 --> 00:16:09.547 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Right.

00:16:09.547 --> 00:16:11.630 align:middle line:84%
>>SIMON: Because he's a
very conservative investor

00:16:11.630 --> 00:16:12.880 align:middle line:90%
and he does it old school way.

00:16:12.880 --> 00:16:15.500 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: So he's moving
away from fiat currency

00:16:15.500 --> 00:16:17.540 align:middle line:90%
and the markets.

00:16:17.540 --> 00:16:21.650 align:middle line:84%
He pulled a lot of money out
of some really solid companies.

00:16:21.650 --> 00:16:25.400 align:middle line:84%
I think he pulled all his money
out of like Southwest Airlines,

00:16:25.400 --> 00:16:28.370 align:middle line:84%
which is, if you're going
to have a people's carrier,

00:16:28.370 --> 00:16:29.420 align:middle line:90%
people mover.

00:16:29.420 --> 00:16:30.155 align:middle line:90%
>>SIMON: Hey, I like Southwest.

00:16:30.155 --> 00:16:30.650 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: I do, too.

00:16:30.650 --> 00:16:31.370 align:middle line:84%
>>SIMON: I flew
here on Southwest.

00:16:31.370 --> 00:16:32.660 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: I fly
them all the time.

00:16:32.660 --> 00:16:35.160 align:middle line:84%
But I mean, even that, I heard
even those conservative guys.

00:16:35.160 --> 00:16:36.020 align:middle line:90%
>>SIMON: And the banks.

00:16:36.020 --> 00:16:37.340 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: And the banks, yeah.

00:16:37.340 --> 00:16:40.390 align:middle line:90%
So he's clearly sensing.

00:16:40.390 --> 00:16:43.330 align:middle line:84%
>>SIMON: He's an
old and wise canary.

00:16:43.330 --> 00:16:45.560 align:middle line:84%
And we should listen
to him singing.

00:16:45.560 --> 00:16:47.200 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yes.

00:16:47.200 --> 00:16:48.970 align:middle line:84%
>>SIMON: But there
are many others.

00:16:48.970 --> 00:16:51.830 align:middle line:84%
Paul Tudor Jones, who is a
very well-known investor,

00:16:51.830 --> 00:16:54.700 align:middle line:84%
he's allocating millions
of dollars into Bitcoin.

00:16:54.700 --> 00:16:56.680 align:middle line:90%
And people went, what?

00:16:56.680 --> 00:16:58.450 align:middle line:84%
But now a bunch of
others have followed.

00:16:58.450 --> 00:17:00.380 align:middle line:90%
So it's happening.

00:17:00.380 --> 00:17:02.350 align:middle line:84%
So the goal of our
conversation here

00:17:02.350 --> 00:17:04.210 align:middle line:84%
is to give some
predictions, but also

00:17:04.210 --> 00:17:06.189 align:middle line:84%
to help people kind
of empower themselves.

00:17:06.189 --> 00:17:07.569 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yes, and prepare.

00:17:07.569 --> 00:17:09.420 align:middle line:84%
>>SIMON: This is not
conspiracy theory,

00:17:09.420 --> 00:17:13.869 align:middle line:84%
this is not like wild crazy
talk meant to disempower you.

00:17:13.869 --> 00:17:16.523 align:middle line:84%
This is so you have
this in mind and you,

00:17:16.523 --> 00:17:18.565 align:middle line:84%
like if you know what the
weather is going to be,

00:17:18.565 --> 00:17:21.609 align:middle line:84%
and you got to drive
somewhere, well, you

00:17:21.609 --> 00:17:24.010 align:middle line:84%
can put on good tires,
you can figure out

00:17:24.010 --> 00:17:25.540 align:middle line:84%
where the hotels
are along the way,

00:17:25.540 --> 00:17:28.390 align:middle line:84%
you can prepare, rather than
just getting in and driving

00:17:28.390 --> 00:17:29.650 align:middle line:90%
and you know.

00:17:29.650 --> 00:17:32.722 align:middle line:84%
So that's the goal here,
is to help empower people.

00:17:32.722 --> 00:17:34.930 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: There are a lot
of creative solutions here.

00:17:34.930 --> 00:17:36.320 align:middle line:90%
We have friends, we have family.

00:17:36.320 --> 00:17:37.120 align:middle line:90%
>>SIMON: Yeah.

00:17:37.120 --> 00:17:39.670 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: We have
places to turn to.

00:17:39.670 --> 00:17:41.350 align:middle line:84%
People have churches
they can turn

00:17:41.350 --> 00:17:43.752 align:middle line:84%
to and larger community
within those churches.

00:17:43.752 --> 00:17:45.460 align:middle line:84%
I think that's where
we have start really

00:17:45.460 --> 00:17:46.900 align:middle line:90%
relying on each other.

00:17:46.900 --> 00:17:48.400 align:middle line:84%
>>SIMON: Community
is the big thing,

00:17:48.400 --> 00:17:50.443 align:middle line:84%
and this is how
traditional cultures live.

00:17:50.443 --> 00:17:51.985 align:middle line:84%
It takes a village
to raise a person.

00:17:51.985 --> 00:17:53.008 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yeah.

00:17:53.008 --> 00:17:54.550 align:middle line:84%
>>SIMON: The other
thing is, it makes

00:17:54.550 --> 00:17:56.830 align:middle line:84%
you really think about what
do you really want to do.

00:17:56.830 --> 00:17:59.163 align:middle line:84%
You've had this corporate job
that you hate, but hey, it

00:17:59.163 --> 00:18:01.370 align:middle line:84%
makes 100k a year, so
I'm not leaving that.

00:18:01.370 --> 00:18:02.170 align:middle line:90%
I hate it.

00:18:02.170 --> 00:18:04.910 align:middle line:84%
Hate the boss, hate my job,
hate the desk, hate the view.

00:18:04.910 --> 00:18:06.190 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Have acid
reflux your waking hours.

00:18:06.190 --> 00:18:06.990 align:middle line:90%
>>SIMON: Right.

00:18:06.990 --> 00:18:09.560 align:middle line:84%
I'm spending half of my
salary just on doctors.

00:18:09.560 --> 00:18:10.360 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yeah.

00:18:10.360 --> 00:18:12.910 align:middle line:84%
>>SIMON: But still, it's
but now you don't have that.

00:18:12.910 --> 00:18:16.687 align:middle line:84%
You can think about, hey,
maybe I should be a gardener.

00:18:16.687 --> 00:18:18.520 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: That's one
of those silver linings

00:18:18.520 --> 00:18:19.420 align:middle line:90%
you're talking about.

00:18:19.420 --> 00:18:21.430 align:middle line:84%
Never been a better time
to just be yourself,

00:18:21.430 --> 00:18:23.620 align:middle line:84%
because the other
stuff isn't available.

00:18:23.620 --> 00:18:23.820 align:middle line:90%
>>SIMON: Yeah.

00:18:23.820 --> 00:18:25.160 align:middle line:84%
And then you attract
the right friends.

00:18:25.160 --> 00:18:27.107 align:middle line:10%
And you yourself, when
you're not yourself,

00:18:27.107 --> 00:18:28.690 align:middle line:10%
I've had those kinds
of jobs and you'd

00:18:28.690 --> 00:18:30.315 align:middle line:10%
have to pretend to
be a certain person,

00:18:30.315 --> 00:18:33.340 align:middle line:10%
and you attract people
who are, they're

00:18:33.340 --> 00:18:34.510 align:middle line:10%
not really your friends.

00:18:34.510 --> 00:18:36.190 align:middle line:84%
And you're not,
and you're always

00:18:36.190 --> 00:18:37.990 align:middle line:90%
vibrating a little stress.

00:18:37.990 --> 00:18:39.330 align:middle line:90%
You're like this.

00:18:39.330 --> 00:18:40.760 align:middle line:90%
And people sense that.

00:18:40.760 --> 00:18:42.820 align:middle line:84%
So when you do what
you're born to do,

00:18:42.820 --> 00:18:45.460 align:middle line:84%
your Dharma, I write about
that in the Dharma books,

00:18:45.460 --> 00:18:47.380 align:middle line:84%
you vibrate a
little differently.

00:18:47.380 --> 00:18:49.398 align:middle line:84%
And yeah, some people
are not going to like it.

00:18:49.398 --> 00:18:50.940 align:middle line:84%
So you're going to
lose some friends.

00:18:50.940 --> 00:18:53.920 align:middle line:84%
You're going to gain the
friends that are right for you,

00:18:53.920 --> 00:18:56.240 align:middle line:84%
and the relationships
that are right for you.

00:18:56.240 --> 00:18:58.990 align:middle line:84%
So that husband or that wife
who thought you were here,

00:18:58.990 --> 00:19:01.160 align:middle line:90%
this person, may go away.

00:19:01.160 --> 00:19:02.713 align:middle line:90%
But hey, that's probably better.

00:19:02.713 --> 00:19:04.630 align:middle line:84%
Be who you are and you'll
attract the husband,

00:19:04.630 --> 00:19:08.260 align:middle line:84%
wife, girlfriend, boyfriend
that is right for you.

00:19:08.260 --> 00:19:09.160 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Right.

00:19:09.160 --> 00:19:12.100 align:middle line:84%
And so people have to be
willing to come into a place,

00:19:12.100 --> 00:19:14.227 align:middle line:84%
also of non-attachment,
because if you have a--

00:19:14.227 --> 00:19:15.310 align:middle line:90%
>>SIMON: It sounds simple.

00:19:15.310 --> 00:19:17.770 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: --fairy tale life
all built up in your mind

00:19:17.770 --> 00:19:20.770 align:middle line:84%
as to how it's all supposed to
go and that is now crumbling.

00:19:20.770 --> 00:19:21.820 align:middle line:90%
>>SIMON: Yeah.

00:19:21.820 --> 00:19:26.850 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: I think, I
feel badly for people

00:19:26.850 --> 00:19:30.780 align:middle line:84%
who have extreme attachments
and concrete expectations,

00:19:30.780 --> 00:19:33.962 align:middle line:84%
because this is not the time,
it's not appropriate really.

00:19:33.962 --> 00:19:36.420 align:middle line:84%
It's not going to work for you
in the time of the outsider.

00:19:36.420 --> 00:19:37.220 align:middle line:90%
>>SIMON: Yeah.

00:19:37.220 --> 00:19:39.825 align:middle line:84%
Well, and that's what a
fairy tale life actually is,

00:19:39.825 --> 00:19:41.650 align:middle line:90%
is tremendous hardship.

00:19:41.650 --> 00:19:44.805 align:middle line:84%
Every fairy tale has
the wicked witch.

00:19:44.805 --> 00:19:46.230 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: That is true.

00:19:46.230 --> 00:19:47.730 align:middle line:84%
>>SIMON: And how
do you defeat them

00:19:47.730 --> 00:19:49.660 align:middle line:90%
through your genuine surrender?

00:19:49.660 --> 00:19:50.460 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yeah.

00:19:50.460 --> 00:19:53.060 align:middle line:84%
>>SIMON: And help from
your community and so on.

00:19:53.060 --> 00:19:55.770 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Or the handsome
prince comes and saves you.

00:19:55.770 --> 00:19:56.670 align:middle line:84%
>>SIMON: That's
true, that's true.

00:19:56.670 --> 00:19:57.540 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: That's another part.

00:19:57.540 --> 00:19:59.460 align:middle line:84%
But that part of the
fairy tale has been

00:19:59.460 --> 00:20:02.760 align:middle line:90%
laid to rest for a while now.

00:20:02.760 --> 00:20:04.520 align:middle line:84%
>>SIMON: The handsome
prince or princess.

00:20:04.520 --> 00:20:05.320 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Whatever.

00:20:05.320 --> 00:20:06.180 align:middle line:90%
>>SIMON: Whatever.

00:20:06.180 --> 00:20:06.750 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Right.

00:20:06.750 --> 00:20:07.550 align:middle line:90%
But you're right.

00:20:07.550 --> 00:20:09.655 align:middle line:84%
Fairy tales, Grimm's fairy
tales always had some.

00:20:09.655 --> 00:20:11.280 align:middle line:84%
>>SIMON: Yes, and
you have to overcome.

00:20:11.280 --> 00:20:12.080 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Darkness

00:20:12.080 --> 00:20:13.770 align:middle line:84%
>>SIMON: That
darkness to get to.

00:20:13.770 --> 00:20:15.958 align:middle line:84%
And usually at the end,
you're a different person.

00:20:15.958 --> 00:20:18.250 align:middle line:84%
So it's a hero myth, like
Joseph Campbell talked about.

00:20:18.250 --> 00:20:18.840 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yes.

00:20:18.840 --> 00:20:20.760 align:middle line:84%
>>SIMON: Like "Star
Wars," which was built

00:20:20.760 --> 00:20:23.700 align:middle line:90%
on Joseph Campbell's teachings.

00:20:23.700 --> 00:20:24.870 align:middle line:90%
You're not the same person.

00:20:24.870 --> 00:20:27.000 align:middle line:84%
Luke Skywalker is
not the same person

00:20:27.000 --> 00:20:29.500 align:middle line:84%
at the end of "Star Wars"
that he was at the beginning.

00:20:29.500 --> 00:20:30.300 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Right.

00:20:30.300 --> 00:20:33.840 align:middle line:84%
>>SIMON: He is a wise
and different individual,

00:20:33.840 --> 00:20:35.100 align:middle line:90%
because of those hardships.

00:20:35.100 --> 00:20:36.720 align:middle line:84%
So that's what a
real fairy tale is.

00:20:36.720 --> 00:20:38.940 align:middle line:84%
You have to go through
it to become who you are,

00:20:38.940 --> 00:20:40.470 align:middle line:90%
who you're born to be.

00:20:40.470 --> 00:20:42.510 align:middle line:84%
And this is the time
of hardship right now,

00:20:42.510 --> 00:20:46.902 align:middle line:84%
especially Jupiter
and Saturn conjuct.

00:20:46.902 --> 00:20:49.110 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Tell us what this
means in layperson terms.

00:20:49.110 --> 00:20:52.500 align:middle line:84%
>>SIMON: In layperson terms, it
means it's a period of Adharma.

00:20:52.500 --> 00:20:59.280 align:middle line:84%
Adharma means a lack of, a
low point in righteousness.

00:20:59.280 --> 00:21:05.160 align:middle line:84%
So fake news seeming real,
real news seeming fake.

00:21:05.160 --> 00:21:09.420 align:middle line:84%
Truth and fiction
being mixed up.

00:21:09.420 --> 00:21:13.310 align:middle line:84%
And our not being able
to see the difference.

00:21:13.310 --> 00:21:18.450 align:middle line:84%
And in Sanskrit there's a
saying, [NON-ENGLISH SPEECH],,

00:21:18.450 --> 00:21:22.650 align:middle line:84%
which says the ability to
discriminate between what is

00:21:22.650 --> 00:21:25.671 align:middle line:84%
and what isn't, what
is real, what is not,

00:21:25.671 --> 00:21:28.120 align:middle line:84%
is the prerequisite
of a spiritual being.

00:21:28.120 --> 00:21:28.920 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yes.

00:21:28.920 --> 00:21:31.500 align:middle line:84%
>>SIMON: You have to
have discrimination.

00:21:31.500 --> 00:21:34.723 align:middle line:84%
Not the discrimination
we talk about on TV.

00:21:34.723 --> 00:21:35.640 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Discernment.

00:21:35.640 --> 00:21:40.133 align:middle line:84%
>>SIMON: Discernment to say
this is real, this isn't.

00:21:40.133 --> 00:21:41.550 align:middle line:84%
Because if you
don't, you're going

00:21:41.550 --> 00:21:43.920 align:middle line:84%
to be led astray by the
next religious leader,

00:21:43.920 --> 00:21:46.867 align:middle line:84%
political leader, fill
in the blank leader.

00:21:46.867 --> 00:21:47.700 align:middle line:90%
And you're going to.

00:21:47.700 --> 00:21:48.930 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Next blogger.

00:21:48.930 --> 00:21:50.597 align:middle line:84%
>>SIMON: Or you're
going to listen to me

00:21:50.597 --> 00:21:53.040 align:middle line:84%
and buy Bitcoin when you
shouldn't and stuff like that.

00:21:53.040 --> 00:21:53.910 align:middle line:90%
Don't listen to me.

00:21:53.910 --> 00:21:54.530 align:middle line:90%
Don't listen to anyone.

00:21:54.530 --> 00:21:56.822 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: We got a fix for
that at the end of the show.

00:21:56.822 --> 00:21:58.890 align:middle line:84%
>>SIMON: You your
discrimination to judge.

00:21:58.890 --> 00:22:01.470 align:middle line:84%
Even the Buddha said, he
said, don't listen to me.

00:22:01.470 --> 00:22:03.900 align:middle line:84%
Go out and test and see
if what I say is true.

00:22:03.900 --> 00:22:04.950 align:middle line:90%
Test it in your life.

00:22:04.950 --> 00:22:07.320 align:middle line:84%
Then come and listen
when you're ready.

00:22:07.320 --> 00:22:08.820 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Well,
interestingly, I did

00:22:08.820 --> 00:22:11.040 align:middle line:84%
a, since I last talked
to you, last interview

00:22:11.040 --> 00:22:13.290 align:middle line:84%
we did, I did one
with Carl Calleman.

00:22:13.290 --> 00:22:17.000 align:middle line:84%
And Carl Calleman is more a
scholar of the Mayan calendar.

00:22:17.000 --> 00:22:18.840 align:middle line:84%
And he said, we're in
this descending phase

00:22:18.840 --> 00:22:21.720 align:middle line:84%
of consciousness right now
and these waves, these wave

00:22:21.720 --> 00:22:26.670 align:middle line:84%
patterns that give way to
not just disinformation,

00:22:26.670 --> 00:22:29.220 align:middle line:90%
but mistrust of one another.

00:22:29.220 --> 00:22:31.380 align:middle line:84%
Not knowing who to
turn to, not knowing

00:22:31.380 --> 00:22:34.860 align:middle line:84%
who's telling the truth, which
gives way to conspiracy theory.

00:22:34.860 --> 00:22:37.230 align:middle line:84%
And what he said that
I found so interesting,

00:22:37.230 --> 00:22:41.310 align:middle line:84%
is he said historically, when
that wave, when that occurs on

00:22:41.310 --> 00:22:47.290 align:middle line:84%
that wave cycle and conspiracy
becomes the mass mind

00:22:47.290 --> 00:22:51.450 align:middle line:84%
set, essentially mistrust
becomes the mass mindset, that

00:22:51.450 --> 00:22:54.490 align:middle line:84%
precipitates the fall of
cultures and civilizations.

00:22:54.490 --> 00:22:55.410 align:middle line:90%
>>SIMON: Yeah, it can.

00:22:55.410 --> 00:22:58.200 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: So how does that
factor into what you're

00:22:58.200 --> 00:22:59.257 align:middle line:90%
saying about this period?

00:22:59.257 --> 00:23:00.840 align:middle line:84%
You're saying the
same thing that he's

00:23:00.840 --> 00:23:04.950 align:middle line:84%
saying right now about the
consciousness of the inability,

00:23:04.950 --> 00:23:10.420 align:middle line:84%
of people's inability to
discern right, truth, so forth.

00:23:10.420 --> 00:23:13.260 align:middle line:84%
>>SIMON: And this also happened
20 years ago, by the way.

00:23:13.260 --> 00:23:19.680 align:middle line:84%
Right around 2001, when we
had the attacks on the towers,

00:23:19.680 --> 00:23:22.618 align:middle line:84%
